  "Process capability compares:": "",
  "Control limits to specification limits": "",
  "Sample means to population means only": "",
  "Cost to revenue": "",
  "Specification limits to process spread (6 sigma)": "",
  "Process capability measures whether the natural process variation (6 sigma) fits within customer specification limits.": "",
  "If a process has sigma = 2 and spec width = 12, the capability index Cp equals:": "",
  "1.0": "",
  "6.0": "",
  "2.0": "",
  "0.5": "",
  "Cp = spec width / 6 sigma = 12 / (6 x 2) = 12/12 = 1.0 (minimally capable).": "",
  "Out-of-control signals include:": "",
  "Points beyond control limits, trends, or non-random patterns": "",
  "Points within limits only": "",
  "Increasing sample size": "",
  "Several patterns signal trouble: points beyond limits, runs above or below the center line, trends, and cyclical patterns.": "",
  "Reducing process variation leads to:": "",
  "No change": "",
  "Improved quality and fewer defects": "",
  "More defects": "",
  "Higher costs always": "",
  "Less variation means more consistent products and fewer items falling outside specifications.": "",
  "What is 'common cause variation'?": "",
  "Random, inherent variation that is natural to a process and always present": "",
  "Variation that should always be eliminated": "",
  "Variation caused by a specific identifiable problem": "",
  "Variation that occurs only in defective products": "",
  "Common cause variation is the natural, random variation inherent in every process. It is expected and predictable.": "",
  "What is 'special cause variation'?": "",
  "Normal random fluctuation": "",
  "Variation that improves the process": "",
  "Variation due to an identifiable, assignable source that should be investigated and removed": "",
  "Variation that never occurs in controlled processes": "",
  "Special cause variation comes from identifiable sources like equipment malfunction, new materials, or operator error.": "",
  "What does 'in statistical control' mean?": "",
  "A process is stable with only common cause variation, and all points fall within control limits with no patterns": "",
  "Someone is physically controlling the machine at all times during production": "",
  "The process never changes under any circumstances or conditions whatsoever": "",
  "The process produces zero defects and every item meets all specifications": "",
  "A process in statistical control exhibits only common cause variation -- points scatter randomly within the control limits.": "",
  "What is 'acceptance sampling'?": "",
  "Testing every single item in a shipment before any of them are released": "",
  "Only inspecting items that look defective based on a visual examination": "",
  "Inspecting a random sample from a lot and deciding whether to accept or reject the entire lot based on the number of defects": "",
  "Accepting all items without inspection and relying on the supplier guarantee": "",
  "Acceptance sampling draws a random sample from a batch and uses the sample results to make an accept/reject decision for the whole lot.": "",
  "What does the 'capability index' (Cp) measure?": "",
  "The cost per defect, which quantifies the financial impact of each nonconforming unit produced": "",
  "The average defect rate, computed by dividing total defects by total items inspected over time": "",
  "The sample size needed for control charts, determined by the desired level of statistical precision": "",
  "The ratio of the specification width to the process width (6 sigma), indicating whether the process can meet specifications": "",
  "Cp = (USL - LSL) / 6 sigma. A Cp of 1 means the process barely fits within specs; higher values indicate better capability.": "",
  "What is the role of the CLT in quality control?": "",
  "It eliminates all variation from the manufacturing process entirely and permanently": "",
  "It is not used in quality control because it applies only to academic statistics": "",
  "It justifies using normal-based control limits for sample means, even when the individual measurements are not normally distributed": "",
  "It increases production speed by reducing the time needed for quality inspections": "",
  "The CLT ensures that sample means are approximately normal for large enough subgroups, justifying the 3-sigma control limits on x-bar charts.": "",
  "What is a 'lot' in acceptance sampling?": "",
  "The control chart": "",
  "The sample that is inspected": "",
  "A single item": "",
  "The entire batch or shipment of items being evaluated": "",
  "The lot is the full batch of items from which a random sample is drawn for inspection.": "",
