  "Manufacturing, healthcare, services, food production, and many other fields": "",
  "Only healthcare settings, where patient safety requires rigorous monitoring": "",
  "Only manufacturing plants, where physical products must meet exact tolerances": "",
  "Only food production facilities, where safety regulations mandate inspections": "",
  "Quality control concepts apply broadly across all industries where consistency and reliability matter.": "",
  "A factory produces ball bearings with a target diameter of 10 mm and sigma = 0.02 mm. Control limits are set at 10 +/- 3(0.02). A sample of 5 bearings has a mean of 10.07 mm. Is the process in control?": "",
  "Cannot be determined without more data": "",
  "No, because 10.07 exceeds the upper control limit of 10.06": "",
  "Yes, because 10.07 is close to 10": "",
  "Yes, because sigma is small": "",
  "UCL = 10 + 3(0.02) = 10.06. Since 10.07 > 10.06, the point is beyond the upper control limit, signaling the process may be out of control.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company samples 100 pills per batch and accepts the batch if no more than 2 pills are defective. If the true defect rate is 1%, what distribution models the number of defective pills?": "",
  "Normal with mu = 1 and sigma = 1": "",
  "Uniform on [0, 100]": "",
  "Binomial with n = 100, p = 0.01 (or Poisson with lambda = 1)": "",
  "Exponential with lambda = 100": "",
  "This is binomial (n = 100, p = 0.01) or well-approximated by Poisson with lambda = np = 1, since n is large and p is small.": "",
  "A bottling plant monitors the proportion of underfilled bottles. Over 20 samples of 50 bottles each, the average proportion defective is 0.04. What are the control limits for a p-chart?": "",
  "0 to 0.50, a very wide interval that would accept almost any defect rate": "",
  "0.04 +/- 3 x sqrt(0.04 x 0.96 / 50) = 0.04 +/- 0.0832, so LCL = 0 and UCL = 0.123": "",
  "0.04 +/- 0.04 = 0 to 0.08, using the proportion itself as the margin of error": "",
  "0.04 +/- 3 x 0.04 = -0.08 to 0.16, using the proportion instead of the standard error": "",
  "SE = sqrt(0.04 x 0.96 / 50) = sqrt(0.000768) = 0.0277. Control limits = 0.04 +/- 3(0.0277) = 0.04 +/- 0.0832. LCL cannot be negative, so LCL = 0, UCL = 0.123.": "",
  "A car manufacturer has specification limits of 2000 +/- 50 for a component dimension. The process has sigma = 15. What is the capability index Cp, and is the process capable?": "",
  "Cp = 2.0, excellent": "",
  "Cp = 100/90 = 1.11, marginally capable": "",
  "Cp = 50/15 = 3.33, highly capable": "",
  "Cp = 0.5, not capable": "",
  "Spec width = 2050 - 1950 = 100. Cp = 100 / (6 x 15) = 100/90 = 1.11. Generally Cp >= 1.33 is desired, so 1.11 is only marginally capable.": "",
  "A candy factory monitors the weight of candy bars. The target is 50g with sigma = 1g. A control chart shows 8 consecutive points all above the center line but within control limits. What should the quality team conclude?": "",
  "The process may be out of control due to a non-random pattern (run), even though all points are within limits": "",
  "The control limits need to be widened": "",
  "This is expected normal variation": "",
  "The process is fine since no points are outside the limits": "",
  "Eight or more consecutive points on one side of the center line is a run, which is a non-random pattern indicating a possible process shift.": "",
  "A circuit board manufacturer has a defect rate of 0.3 defects per board. Using the Poisson distribution, what is the probability a randomly selected board has zero defects?": "",
  "0.259": "",
  "0.500": "",
  "0.300": "",
  "0.741": "",
  "P(X = 0) = e^(-0.3) = 0.7408. About 74.1% of boards are defect-free.": "",
  "A food company uses acceptance sampling. They inspect 20 items from a lot and reject the lot if more than 1 item is defective. If the true defect rate is 5%, what is the probability the lot is accepted?": "",
  "0.950": "",
  "0.264": "",
  "0.736": "",
  "0.358": "",
  "P(accept) = P(X <= 1) = P(0) + P(1). P(0) = (0.95)^20 = 0.3585. P(1) = C(20,1)(0.05)(0.95)^19 = 20 x 0.05 x 0.3774 = 0.3774. Total = 0.3585 + 0.3774 = 0.736.": "",
  "A semiconductor fab tracks the number of particles per wafer. The process averages 2 particles per wafer. Management wants no more than 5 particles on any wafer. What is the probability a wafer passes this criterion?": "",
  "0.50": "",
  "0.9834": "",
  "0.9500": "",
  "0.8571": "",
  "Using Poisson with lambda = 2: P(X <= 5) = sum of P(0) through P(5) = 0.1353 + 0.2707 + 0.2707 + 0.1804 + 0.0902 + 0.0361 = 0.9834.": "",
  "A hospital monitors surgical site infections. The historical rate is 2% of surgeries. In a month with 200 surgeries, 8 infections occur. Using the expected value and control chart logic, is this unusual?": "",
  "Borderline: expected = 4, and 8 is 2 SDs above expected (z = 2.0), which warrants investigation": "",
  "Yes, 8 is more than double the expected, so the hospital should close": "",
  "Cannot determine without more data": "",
  "No, 8 out of 200 is normal": "",
  "Expected = np = 200 x 0.02 = 4. SD = sqrt(200 x 0.02 x 0.98) = sqrt(3.92) = 1.98. z = (8 - 4)/1.98 = 2.0. This is at the 2-sigma level, warranting investigation.": "",
  "A coffee shop targets 12 oz per cup with sigma = 0.5 oz. The specification limits are 11 oz to 13 oz. What is the Cp, and what percentage of cups are expected to fall outside specifications?": "",
  "Cp = 2.0; virtually none outside specifications": "",
  "Cp = 0.67; about 4.6% outside specifications": "",
  "Cp = 1.0; about 0.3% outside specifications": "",
  "Cp = 0.33; about 50% outside specifications": "",
  "Cp = (13 - 11) / (6 x 0.5) = 2/3 = 0.67. The specs are at mu +/- 2 sigma, so about 4.6% fall outside (since about 95.4% are within 2 sigma).": ""
